             "To create a function that pushes all values into a heap and \
then pops off the smallest values one at a time, we can use Python's `heapq` \
module, which provides an efficient way to implement a min-heap.\n\nHere\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a concise implementation:\n\n```python\nimport heapq\n\n\
def process_heap(values):\n    # Create a min-heap from the input values\n    \
heap = []\n    for value in values:\n        heapq.heappush(heap, value)\n    \
\n    # Pop off the smallest values one at a time\n    sorted_values = []\n   \
 while heap:\n        smallest = heapq.heappop(heap)\n        \
sorted_values.append(smallest)\n    \n    return sorted_values\n\n# Example \
usage:\nvalues = [5, 2, 9, 1, 5, 6]\nsorted_values = process_heap(values)\n\
print(sorted_values)  # Output: [1, 2, 5, 5, 6, 9]\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n\
1. We import the `heapq` module.\n2. We define the `process_heap` function \
that takes a list of values.\n3. We create an empty list `heap` to serve as \
our min-heap.\n4. We push each value into the heap using `heapq.heappush`.\n\
5. We pop the smallest values from the heap until it is empty, collecting \
these in `sorted_values`.\n6. Finally, we return the sorted list of \
values."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {400, Automatic}], "Tooltip"]& ], 
