              "\"To find the first digit of the factorial of a given number, \
we can use logarithms to avoid calculating the large factorial directly. Here\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s a concise Python function to achieve that:\\n\\n```python\
\\nimport math\\n\\ndef first_digit_of_factorial(n):\\n    if n == 0 or n == \
1:\\n        return 1  # 0! = 1! = 1\\n\\n    # Calculate log10 of factorial \
using the property: log10(n!) = log10(1) + log10(2) + ... + log10(n)\\n    \
log_sum = sum(math.log10(i) for i in range(1, n + 1))\\n    \\n    # Get the \
first digit\\n    first_digit = int(10 ** (log_sum - int(log_sum)))\\n    \
return first_digit\\n\\n# Example usage\\nprint(first_digit_of_factorial(5))  \
# Output: 1 (since 5! = 120)\\nprint(first_digit_of_factorial(10)) # Output: \
3 (since 10! = 3628800)\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. **Base Cases**: \
Handle the cases for 0! and 1!.\\n2. **Logarithm Calculation**: Use the \
property of logarithms to compute the sum of the logarithms of integers up to \
`n`.\\n3. **Extract First Digit**: Use the fractional part of the logarithm \
sum to compute the first digit by raising 10 to that power and taking the \
integer part.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
