              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"You can use the `collections` module to remove duplicate \
words from a string effectively. Here's a simple function that does that \
using `collections.OrderedDict` to maintain the order of words while removing \
duplicates:\\n\\n```python\\nfrom collections import OrderedDict\\n\\ndef \
remove_duplicate_words(input_string):\\n    # Split the string into words\\n  \
  words = input_string.split()\\n    # Use OrderedDict to remove duplicates \
while maintaining order\\n    unique_words = OrderedDict.fromkeys(words)\\n   \
 # Join the unique words back into a string\\n    result = ' \
'.join(unique_words)\\n    return result\\n\\n# Example usage:\\ninput_str = \
\\\"hello world world hello python python\\\"\\noutput_str = \
remove_duplicate_words(input_str)\\nprint(output_str)  # Output: \\\"hello \
world python\\\"\\n```\\n\\nThis function takes an input string, splits it \
into words, removes duplicates, and returns a string with unique words in \
their original order.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
