          PointBox[{{2.1751579347204997`, 10.59269664573042}}]}, 
         PaneBox[
          TagBox[
           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to find the equilibrium index of the given \
array.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Certainly! An equilibrium index in an array is an index such \
that the sum of elements at lower indices is equal to the sum of elements at \
higher indices.\\n\\nHere is a Python function to find the equilibrium index \
of a given array:\\n\\n```python\\ndef find_equilibrium_index(arr):\\n    \
total_sum = sum(arr)  # Calculate total sum of the array\\n    left_sum = 0  \
# Initialize left sum for elements before the current index\\n\\n    for i, \
num in enumerate(arr):\\n        total_sum -= num  # Now total_sum is the sum \
of elements right of index i\\n        \\n        if left_sum == total_sum:  \
# Check if left sum is equal to total sum\\n            return i  # \
Equilibrium index found\\n        \\n        left_sum += num  # Update left \
sum for next iteration\\n    \\n    return -1  # Return -1 if no equilibrium \
index is found\\n\\n# Example usage:\\narr = [1, 3, 5, 2, 2]\\nindex = \
find_equilibrium_index(arr)\\nprint(f\\\"The equilibrium index is: \
{index}\\\")\\n```\\n\\nThis function iterates through the array while \
maintaining a `left_sum` and adjusting the `total_sum` to represent the sum \
of elements to the right of the current index. If at any index the `left_sum` \
equals the `total_sum`, it returns that index as the equilibrium index. If no \
such index is found, it returns -1.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to find the equilibrium index of the given \
array."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "Certainly! An equilibrium index in an array is an index such \
that the sum of elements at lower indices is equal to the sum of elements at \
higher indices.\n\nHere is a Python function to find the equilibrium index of \
a given array:\n\n```python\ndef find_equilibrium_index(arr):\n    total_sum \
= sum(arr)  # Calculate total sum of the array\n    left_sum = 0  # \
Initialize left sum for elements before the current index\n\n    for i, num \
in enumerate(arr):\n        total_sum -= num  # Now total_sum is the sum of \
elements right of index i\n        \n        if left_sum == total_sum:  # \
Check if left sum is equal to total sum\n            return i  # Equilibrium \
index found\n        \n        left_sum += num  # Update left sum for next \
iteration\n    \n    return -1  # Return -1 if no equilibrium index is found\n\
\n# Example usage:\narr = [1, 3, 5, 2, 2]\nindex = \
find_equilibrium_index(arr)\nprint(f\"The equilibrium index is: {index}\")\n\
```\n\nThis function iterates through the array while maintaining a \
`left_sum` and adjusting the `total_sum` to represent the sum of elements to \
the right of the current index. If at any index the `left_sum` equals the \
`total_sum`, it returns that index as the equilibrium index. If no such index \
is found, it returns -1."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {400, Automatic}], 
         "Tooltip"]& ], 
       TagBox[
        TooltipBox[{
          Opacity[0.], 
          PointBox[{{2.284696402082704, 11.125149154019493`}}]}, 
