              "\"To determine whether one array is a subset of another, you \
can implement a function in Python that checks if all elements of the first \
array (subset) exist in the second array (superset). Here's how you can do \
it:\\n\\n```python\\ndef is_subset(small, large):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    \
Check if the array `small` is a subset of the array `large`.\\n\\n    \
Parameters:\\n    small (list): The array to check if it is a subset.\\n    \
large (list): The array to check against.\\n\\n    Returns:\\n    bool: True \
if `small` is a subset of `large`, False otherwise.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    \
# Convert large array to a set for O(1) average-time complexity lookups\\n    \
large_set = set(large)\\n    \\n    # Check each element in `small` to see if \
it is in `large_set`\\n    for element in small:\\n        if element not in \
large_set:\\n            return False\\n    \\n    return True\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nsmall_array = [1, 2, 3]\\nlarge_array = [1, 2, 3, 4, \
5]\\nprint(is_subset(small_array, large_array))  # Output: \
True\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. **Convert the Large Array to a Set**: \
By converting the `large` array into a set (`large_set`), you can leverage \
the average O(1) time complexity for membership checks in a set.\\n2. \
**Iterate Over the Small Array**: For each element in the `small` array, \
check if it exists in the `large_set`.\\n3. **Return the Result**: If any \
element in `small` is not found in `large_set`, return `False`. If all \
elements are found, return `True`.\\n\\nThis approach efficiently checks \
subset membership and works well for reasonably sized arrays.\""}}, 
