             "To create a Python function that checks whether the product of \
digits at even and odd positions in a number is equal, follow these steps:\n\n\
1. Convert the number to a string to easily access each digit.\n2. Iterate \
over the digits, distinguishing between even and odd positions.\n3. Calculate \
the product of digits at even positions and the product of digits at odd \
positions.\n4. Compare the two products and return the result.\n\nHere's the \
implementation:\n\n```python\ndef check_even_odd_product_equal(number):\n    \
# Convert the number to a string to access digits by position\n    num_str = \
str(number)\n    \n    # Initialize products for even and odd positions\n    \
product_even = 1\n    product_odd = 1\n    \n    # Iterate over the string, \
finding the position and digit\n    for index, digit in enumerate(num_str):\n \
       # Convert character back to an integer\n        digit = int(digit)\n   \
     \n        # Check if the position is odd or even (0-based index)\n       \
 if index % 2 == 0:\n            # 0-based: even index means odd position \
(1-based)\n            product_odd *= digit\n        else:\n            # \
0-based: odd index means even position (1-based)\n            product_even *= \
digit\n    \n    # Return True if both products are equal, False otherwise\n  \
  return product_even == product_odd\n\n# Example usage\n\
print(check_even_odd_product_equal(1234))  # Output: False\n\
print(check_even_odd_product_equal(1212))  # Output: True\n```\n\nThis \
function will compute the products of digits at odd and even positions and \
compare them, returning `True` if they are equal and `False` otherwise. Note \
that \"position\" here is based on 1-based indexing as humans would count, \
