Python, you can implement this using the `re` module. Here's a function that \
performs this match:\\n\\n```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef \
match_ab_pattern(string):\\n    # Define the regex pattern for 'a' followed \
by zero or more 'b's\\n    pattern = r'^ab*$'\\n    \\n    # Use re.match to \
check if the entire string matches the pattern\\n    if re.match(pattern, \
string):\\n        return True\\n    else:\\n        return False\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\nprint(match_ab_pattern(\\\"a\\\"))      # \
True\\nprint(match_ab_pattern(\\\"ab\\\"))     # \
True\\nprint(match_ab_pattern(\\\"abb\\\"))    # \
True\\nprint(match_ab_pattern(\\\"ac\\\"))     # \
False\\nprint(match_ab_pattern(\\\"aabb\\\"))   # False\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n- The pattern `^ab*$` is used:\\n  - `^` asserts the start of \
the string.\\n  - `a` matches the character \\\"a\\\".\\n  - `b*` matches \
zero or more occurrences of the character \\\"b\\\".\\n  - `$` asserts the \
end of the string.\\n- `re.match()` checks if the entire string matches the \
specified pattern. If it does, the function returns `True`. Otherwise, it \
returns `False`.\""}}, 
