              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To solve this problem, we can use dynamic programming to \
find a path with the maximum average from the top-left corner to the \
bottom-right corner of an \\\\( n \\\\times n \\\\) matrix. The path consists \
of moving only right or down at each step.\\n\\nHere's a Python function to \
find such a path:\\n\\n```python\\ndef max_average_path(matrix):\\n    if not \
matrix or not matrix[0]:\\n        return 0\\n\\n    n = len(matrix)\\n    dp \
= [[0] * n for _ in range(n)]\\n    \\n    # Initialize the starting point\\n \
   dp[0][0] = matrix[0][0]\\n\\n    # Fill the first row (can only come from \
the left)\\n    for j in range(1, n):\\n        dp[0][j] = dp[0][j - 1] + \
matrix[0][j]\\n\\n    # Fill the first column (can only come from above)\\n   \
 for i in range(1, n):\\n        dp[i][0] = dp[i - 1][0] + matrix[i][0]\\n\\n \
   # Fill the rest of the dp table\\n    for i in range(1, n):\\n        for \
j in range(1, n):\\n            dp[i][j] = max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]) + \
matrix[i][j]\\n\\n    # The total maximum sum path is in dp[n-1][n-1]\\n    \
max_sum = dp[n - 1][n - 1]\\n\\n    # Calculate the number of steps in the \
path\\n    steps = (n - 1) * 2\\n\\n    # Calculate the maximum average\\n    \
max_average = max_sum / (steps + 1)\\n\\n    return max_average\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\nmatrix = [\\n    [5, 1, 0],\\n    [2, 3, 4],\\n    [5, 6, 1]\
\\n]\\nprint(max_average_path(matrix))  # Output will be the maximum average \
over a path\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n\\n1. **Dynamic Programming Table \
(`dp`)**: \\n   - `dp[i][j]` represents the maximum sum of the path from the \
top-left corner to the cell `(i, j)`.\\n\\n2. **Initialization**:\\n   - \
Start with `dp[0][0]` equal to `matrix[0][0]`.\\n   - The first row can \
only\""}}, GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
