              "\"To count the same pairs in two given lists using the `map` \
function, you can follow these steps:\\n\\n1. Use the `map` function to \
iterate over both lists simultaneously.\\n2. Compare the pairs from both \
lists.\\n3. Sum the results to get the total count of matching \
pairs.\\n\\nHere's a Python function that does this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
count_same_pairs(list1, list2):\\n    # Use map to compare elements from both \
lists\\n    # Use zip to pair elements from list1 and list2\\n    # Sum the \
boolean results (True is 1, False is 0)\\n    return sum(map(lambda x, y: x \
== y, list1, list2))\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nlist1 = [1, 2, 3, 4]\\nlist2 = \
[1, 2, 0, 4]\\nprint(count_same_pairs(list1, list2))  # Output: \
3\\n```\\n\\n**Explanation**:\\n- `zip(list1, list2)` pairs up elements from \
both lists.\\n- `map(lambda x, y: x == y, list1, list2)` applies the lambda \
function to each pair from the zipped lists, returning `True` if the elements \
are equal and `False` otherwise.\\n- `sum(...)` adds up all the `True` (1) \
values to get the count of matching pairs.\""}}, 
