              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To extract values between quotation marks using regular \
expressions in Python, you can use the `re` module. Here is a function that \
achieves this:\\n\\n```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef \
extract_quoted_strings(input_string):\\n    # Regular expression pattern to \
match text within quotes\\n    pattern = r'\\\"(.*?)\\\"'\\n    # Find all \
matches in the input string\\n    matches = re.findall(pattern, input_string)\
\\n    return matches\\n\\n# Example usage:\\ninput_str = 'She said, \
\\\"Hello, world!\\\" and then \\\"Goodbye, world!\\\"'\\nresult = \
extract_quoted_strings(input_str)\\nprint(result)  # Output: ['Hello, \
world!', 'Goodbye, world!']\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- The pattern `r'\\\
\"(.*?)\\\"'` is used to match any text that is enclosed within double \
quotation marks.\\n  - `\\\"` matches the literal double-quote character.\\n  \
- `(.*?)` is a non-greedy match for any character (`.`) zero or more times \
(`*`), capturing the smallest possible string.\\n- `re.findall()` returns all \
non-overlapping matches of the pattern in the input string as a list.\\n- The \
function returns this list of matches.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to extract values between quotation marks of \
