             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To extract values between quotation marks using regular \
expressions in Python, you can use the `re` module. Here is a function that \
achieves this:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef \
extract_quoted_strings(input_string):\n    # Regular expression pattern to \
match text within quotes\n    pattern = r'\"(.*?)\"'\n    # Find all matches \
in the input string\n    matches = re.findall(pattern, input_string)\n    \
return matches\n\n# Example usage:\ninput_str = 'She said, \"Hello, world!\" \
and then \"Goodbye, world!\"'\nresult = extract_quoted_strings(input_str)\n\
print(result)  # Output: ['Hello, world!', 'Goodbye, world!']\n```\n\n### \
Explanation:\n- The pattern `r'\"(.*?)\"'` is used to match any text that is \
enclosed within double quotation marks.\n  - `\"` matches the literal \
double-quote character.\n  - `(.*?)` is a non-greedy match for any character \
(`.`) zero or more times (`*`), capturing the smallest possible string.\n- \
`re.findall()` returns all non-overlapping matches of the pattern in the \
input string as a list.\n- The function returns this list of matches."}}, 
