              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the sum of products of all possible subarrays, we \
can iterate through each element of the array and calculate the contribution \
of each element in all the subarrays that include it. Here's a Python \
function to achieve this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
sum_of_products_of_subarrays(arr):\\n    n = len(arr)\\n    total_sum = 0\\n  \
  \\n    # Iterate over each element in the array\\n    for i in range(n):\\n \
       # The number of subarrays that include arr[i] is (i + 1) * (n - i)\\n  \
      # This is because arr[i] can be the end of (i + 1) subarrays starting \
from any index <= i\\n        # and the start of (n - i) subarrays ending at \
any index >= i.\\n        contribution = arr[i] * (i + 1) * (n - i)\\n        \
total_sum += contribution\\n    \\n    return total_sum\\n\\n# Example usage:\
\\narr = [1, 2, 3]\\nprint(sum_of_products_of_subarrays(arr))  # Output: \
20\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n\\n- For each element `arr[i]`, count how \
many subarrays include `arr[i]`.\\n- The element `arr[i]` is included in `(i \
+ 1) * (n - i)` subarrays:\\n  - `(i + 1)` ways to choose the starting index \
of the subarray such that it includes `arr[i]`.\\n  - `(n - i)` ways to \
choose the ending index of the subarray such that it includes `arr[i]`.\\n- \
Multiply `arr[i]` by this count to get its contribution to the total sum of \
products.\\n- Sum all contributions for the final result.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
