number to its binary representation.\n2. Leave the first and last bits \
unchanged.\n3. Toggle all bits in between.\n4. Convert the modified binary \
representation back to a decimal number.\n\nHere's the Python function \
implementing these steps:\n\n```python\ndef toggle_bits_except_first_last(n):\
\n    # Get the binary representation of the number as a string, strip the \
'0b' prefix\n    binary = bin(n)[2:]\n    \n    # If the number has 2 or \
fewer bits, no toggling is needed\n    if len(binary) <= 2:\n        return n\
\n    \n    # First and last bits remain the same\n    first_bit = binary[0]\n\
    last_bit = binary[-1]\n    \n    # Toggle the bits in between\n    \
toggled_middle = ''.join('1' if bit == '0' else '0' for bit in binary[1:-1])\n\
    \n    # Construct the new binary string\n    toggled_binary = first_bit + \
toggled_middle + last_bit\n    \n    # Convert the toggled binary string back \
to an integer\n    return int(toggled_binary, 2)\n\n# Example usage:\nnumber \
= 29  # Binary: 11101\nresult = toggle_bits_except_first_last(number)\n\
print(result)  # Output will be 23, Binary: 10111\n```\n\nThis function will \
correctly toggle all bits of the number except the first and last one. You \
