             "To achieve this, you can use a regular expression to identify \
where a capital letter follows a lowercase letter or another capital letter \
without a space. Here's a Python function that accomplishes this:\n\n\
```python\nimport re\n\ndef add_spaces_to_camel_case(text):\n    # Use a \
regular expression to find positions where a capital letter follows a \
lowercase letter\n    # or another capital letter without a space in between.\
\n    result = re.sub(r'(?<=[a-z])(?=[A-Z])|(?<=[A-Z])(?=[A-Z][a-z])', ' ', \
text)\n    return result\n\n# Example usage\ninput_string = \
\"ThisIsACamelCaseString\"\noutput_string = \
add_spaces_to_camel_case(input_string)\nprint(output_string)  # Output: \
\"This Is A Camel Case String\"\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- The regular \
expression `(?<=[a-z])(?=[A-Z])` matches positions where a lowercase letter \
is followed by an uppercase letter.\n- The regular expression \
`(?<=[A-Z])(?=[A-Z][a-z])` matches positions where an uppercase letter is \
followed by another uppercase letter and then a lowercase letter (to handle \
multiple capital letters like in \"JSONData\").\n- The `re.sub()` function \
inserts a space at each match.\n\nThis function will correctly handle \
camelCase and PascalCase strings, inserting spaces appropriately."}}, 
