             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To determine if a given array represents a min heap, you need \
to verify that each parent node is less than or equal to its child nodes. In \
a 0-based index array representation of a heap, for a node at index `i`, the \
left child is at index `2i + 1` and the right child is at index `2i + 2`. \n\n\
Here's a Python function to check if an array represents a min heap:\n\n\
```python\ndef is_min_heap(arr):\n    n = len(arr)\n    \n    # Start from \
the first internal node who has children, which is at n//2 - 1\n    for i in \
range(n // 2):\n        left_child = 2 * i + 1\n        right_child = 2 * i + \
2\n        \n        # Check if the left child is greater than the parent\n   \
     if left_child < n and arr[i] > arr[left_child]:\n            return \
False\n        \n        # Check if the right child is greater than the \
parent\n        if right_child < n and arr[i] > arr[right_child]:\n           \
 return False\n    \n    return True\n\n# Example usage:\n# arr = [1, 3, 5, \
7, 9, 8]\n# print(is_min_heap(arr))  # Output: True\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n\
