              "\"To write a function that matches a string containing an 'a' \
followed by zero or one 'b', you can use a regular expression. In Python, you \
can achieve this using the `re` module. The regular expression pattern for \
this requirement is `ab?`, where `a` is followed by zero or one `b` \
(indicated by `b?`).\\n\\nHere's how you can implement this in \
Python:\\n\\n```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef \
match_a_followed_by_zero_or_one_b(s):\\n    # Define the regular expression \
pattern\\n    pattern = r'ab?'\\n    \\n    # Use re.fullmatch to check if \
the entire string matches the pattern\\n    return re.fullmatch(pattern, s) \
is not None\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nprint(match_a_followed_by_zero_or_one_b('a'))   # \
True\\nprint(match_a_followed_by_zero_or_one_b('ab'))  # \
True\\nprint(match_a_followed_by_zero_or_one_b('abb')) # \
False\\nprint(match_a_followed_by_zero_or_one_b('b'))   # \
False\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- `ab?` is the regex pattern where:\\n  - \
`a` matches the character 'a'.\\n  - `b?` matches zero or one occurrence of \
the character 'b'.\\n- `re.fullmatch()` is used to ensure that the entire \
string `s` matches the pattern, not just a part of it.\\n\\nThis function \
returns `True` if the input string matches the pattern (i.e., it is exactly \
'a' or 'ab'), otherwise, it returns `False`.\""}}, 
