              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to count number of unique lists within a \
list.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To count the number of unique lists within a list, you can \
use Python's capabilities to convert lists to tuples (since lists are mutable \
and cannot be directly added to a set) and then use a set to determine \
uniqueness. Here's a function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
count_unique_lists(list_of_lists):\\n    # Convert each inner list to a tuple \
(since tuples are hashable and can be added to a set)\\n    tuple_set = \
set(tuple(sublist) for sublist in list_of_lists)\\n    \\n    # The number of \
unique lists is the size of the set\\n    return len(tuple_set)\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\nlist_of_lists = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [1, 2], [5, 6], [3, \
4]]\\nprint(count_unique_lists(list_of_lists))  # Output: 3\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n1. **Conversion to Tuples**: Each list is converted to a tuple \
because tuples are hashable and can be stored in a set, whereas lists cannot.\
\\n2. **Set for Uniqueness**: A set automatically handles duplicates, so \
adding elements to a set will only store unique elements.\\n3. **Count Unique \
Elements**: The length of the set gives the number of unique lists.\\n\\nThis \
function assumes that the lists contain elements that can be converted and \
compared as tuples.\""}}, 
