          Opacity[0.], 
          PointBox[{{3.031367188878535, 10.234135955444097`}}]}, 
         PaneBox[
          TagBox[
           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to iterate over all pairs of consecutive \
items in a given list.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To iterate over all pairs of consecutive items in a given \
list, you can define a function using a simple loop. Here's a Python function \
to achieve this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef iterate_consecutive_pairs(lst):\\n    \
for i in range(len(lst) - 1):\\n        yield (lst[i], lst[i + 1])\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\nexample_list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\\nfor pair in \
iterate_consecutive_pairs(example_list):\\n    print(pair)\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n- The function `iterate_consecutive_pairs(lst)` takes a list \
`lst` as input.\\n- It uses a `for` loop to iterate over indices from `0` to \
`len(lst) - 2`.\\n- For each index `i`, it yields a tuple containing the \
element at index `i` and the element at index `i + 1`.\\n- This creates pairs \
of consecutive elements from the list.\\n- The `yield` keyword allows the \
function to be a generator, producing pairs one at a time.\\n\\n### Example \
Output:\\nFor the list `[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]`, the output pairs would \
be:\\n```\\n(1, 2)\\n(2, 3)\\n(3, 4)\\n(4, 5)\\n```\\n\\nThis approach is \
efficient and works for any list with at least two elements. If the list has \
fewer than two elements, the function will naturally produce no output.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to iterate over all pairs of consecutive items \
in a given list."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To iterate over all pairs of consecutive items in a given list, \
you can define a function using a simple loop. Here's a Python function to \
achieve this:\n\n```python\ndef iterate_consecutive_pairs(lst):\n    for i in \
range(len(lst) - 1):\n        yield (lst[i], lst[i + 1])\n\n# Example usage:\n\
example_list = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nfor pair in \
iterate_consecutive_pairs(example_list):\n    print(pair)\n```\n\n### \
Explanation:\n- The function `iterate_consecutive_pairs(lst)` takes a list \
`lst` as input.\n- It uses a `for` loop to iterate over indices from `0` to \
`len(lst) - 2`.\n- For each index `i`, it yields a tuple containing the \
element at index `i` and the element at index `i + 1`.\n- This creates pairs \
of consecutive elements from the list.\n- The `yield` keyword allows the \
function to be a generator, producing pairs one at a time.\n\n### Example \
Output:\nFor the list `[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]`, the output pairs would be:\n```\n(1, \
2)\n(2, 3)\n(3, 4)\n(4, 5)\n```\n\nThis approach is efficient and works for \
any list with at least two elements. If the list has fewer than two elements, \
the function will naturally produce no output."}}, 
