   \\n    # Join the filtered words back into a string\\n    result = ' \
'.join(filtered_words)\\n    \\n    return result\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nexample_string = \\\"This is a test string with some words\\\"\\nk = \
4\\nprint(remove_words_with_length_k(example_string, k))\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n- **Splitting the String**: The input string is split into a \
list of words using `split()`.\\n- **Filtering**: A list comprehension is \
used to create a list of words that do not have the specified length \\\\( k \
\\\\).\\n- **Joining**: The filtered list of words is joined back into a \
single string using `join()`.\\n- **Return**: The resulting string, which \
excludes words of length \\\\( k \\\\), is returned.\\n\\n### Example \
Usage:\\nFor the input string `\\\"This is a test string with some words\\\"` \
and \\\\( k = 4 \\\\), the function will output `\\\"This is a string \
some\\\"`, removing `\\\"test\\\"` and `\\\"with\\\"`, which are both 4 \
characters long.\""}}, 
