substring\n        start = main_string.find(substring, start)\n        \n     \
   # If find() returns -1, there are no more occurrences\n        if start == \
-1:\n            break\n        \n        # Append the position to the list\n \
       occurrences.append(start)\n        \n        # Move to the next \
character after the current found position\n        start += 1\n    \n    \
return occurrences\n\n# Example usage:\nmain_string = \"This is a test \
string. Testing is essential for tests.\"\nsubstring = \"test\"\npositions = \
find_substring_occurrences(main_string, substring)\nprint(\"Occurrences of \
substring:\", positions)\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- The function \
`find_substring_occurrences` takes two parameters: `main_string` (the string \
to search within) and `substring` (the substring to find).\n- An empty list \
`occurrences` is initialized to store the positions of each occurrence.\n- A \
`while` loop is used to repeatedly search for the substring starting from the \
last found position.\n- The `find` method returns the lowest index where the \
substring is found, or `-1` if it is not found.\n- When an occurrence is \
found, its index is appended to the `occurrences` list.\n- The `start` \
variable is incremented by 1 to continue searching for subsequent \
occurrences.\n- The loop breaks when no more occurrences are found (`start == \
