              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To count the number of unique lists within a list in Python, \
you can use the following function. This function assumes that the inner \
lists are hashable, which means they contain only hashable elements (e.g., \
integers, strings, tuples, etc.):\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
count_unique_lists(list_of_lists):\\n    # Convert each list to a tuple to \
make them hashable\\n    tuples = [tuple(lst) for lst in list_of_lists]\\n    \
# Use a set to find unique tuples\\n    unique_tuples = set(tuples)\\n    # \
Return the number of unique tuples\\n    return len(unique_tuples)\\n\\n# \
Example usage:\\nlist_of_lists = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [1, 2], [5, \
6]]\\nprint(count_unique_lists(list_of_lists))  # Output: 3\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function works by converting each list to a tuple (since lists themselves are \
not hashable), adding these tuples to a set (which automatically handles \
uniqueness), and then returning the size of the set.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
