              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To determine whether the count of divisors of a given number \
is even or odd, we can use the following observation: \\n\\nA number has an \
odd number of divisors if and only if it is a perfect square. This is because \
divisors typically come in pairs (e.g., for 12, the pairs are (1, 12), (2, \
6), (3, 4)). However, in the case of a perfect square, one of the divisors is \
repeated as a pair (e.g., for 9, the divisors are (1, 9), (3, 3)).\\n\\nHere \
is a Python function to check whether the count of divisors is even or \
odd:\\n\\n```python\\ndef is_divisor_count_even(n):\\n    if n <= 0:\\n       \
 raise ValueError(\\\"Input must be a positive integer.\\\")\\n    # Check if \
n is a perfect square\\n    root = int(n**0.5)\\n    if root * root == n:\\n  \
      return False  # Odd count of divisors\\n    else:\\n        return True \
 # Even count of divisors\\n\\n# Example usage:\\n# \
print(is_divisor_count_even(12))  # Output: True (even)\\n# \
print(is_divisor_count_even(9))   # Output: False (odd)\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function determines if the number is a perfect square by comparing the square \
of the integer square root with the original number. If they are equal, the \
number is a perfect square, and thus the divisor count is odd. Otherwise, the \
count is even.\""}}, 
