7]\\nprint(product_of_first_even_and_odd(numbers))  # Output: \
6\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- The function initializes `first_even` and \
`first_odd` to `None`.\\n- It iterates through the list, checking each \
number.\\n- If it finds an even number and `first_even` is `None`, it assigns \
this number to `first_even`.\\n- Similarly, if it finds an odd number and \
`first_odd` is `None`, it assigns this number to `first_odd`.\\n- Once both \
`first_even` and `first_odd` are found, it breaks out of the loop and returns \
their product.\\n- If the list does not contain at least one even and one odd \
number, the function returns `None`.\""}}, 
