              "\"To convert a tuple represented as a string to an actual \
integer tuple, you can use Python's `ast.literal_eval` function from the \
`ast` module, which safely evaluates a string containing a Python literal \
expression. Here's how you can write a function to achieve \
this:\\n\\n```python\\nimport ast\\n\\ndef \
convert_tuple_string_to_int_tuple(tuple_string):\\n    try:\\n        # \
Safely evaluate the string as a Python literal\\n        result = \
ast.literal_eval(tuple_string)\\n        # Check if the result is a tuple and \
contains only integers\\n        if isinstance(result, tuple) and \
all(isinstance(x, int) for x in result):\\n            return result\\n       \
 else:\\n            raise ValueError(\\\"The input string does not represent \
a tuple of integers.\\\")\\n    except (ValueError, SyntaxError):\\n        \
raise ValueError(\\\"Invalid input: unable to convert string to integer \
tuple.\\\")\\n\\n# Example usage:\\ntuple_str = \\\"(1, 2, 3)\\\"\\nint_tuple \
= convert_tuple_string_to_int_tuple(tuple_str)\\nprint(int_tuple)  # Output: \
(1, 2, 3)\\n```\\n\\nThis function will:\\n\\n1. Use `ast.literal_eval` to \
safely parse the string as a Python literal.\\n2. Check that the result is a \
tuple and contains only integers.\\n3. Return the integer tuple if valid, or \
raise a `ValueError` if the input is not valid.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
