              "\"To locate the right insertion point for a specified value in \
a sorted list, you can use the `bisect` module in Python, specifically the \
`bisect_right` function. This function returns the index where the specified \
value should be inserted to maintain sorted order, such that if the value is \
already present, it is inserted after the existing values.\\n\\nHere's a \
sample function demonstrating how to use \
`bisect_right`:\\n\\n```python\\nimport bisect\\n\\ndef \
find_right_insertion_point(sorted_list, value):\\n    # Use bisect_right to \
find the right insertion point\\n    return bisect.bisect_right(sorted_list, \
value)\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nsorted_list = [1, 2, 4, 4, \
5]\\nvalue_to_insert = 4\\ninsertion_point = \
find_right_insertion_point(sorted_list, \
value_to_insert)\\nprint(insertion_point)  # Output will be 4\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function takes a sorted list and a value, and it returns the index where the \
value should be inserted to maintain the sorted order with any duplicates \
appearing to the left.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
