              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To remove a nested record (such as a list or another tuple) \
from a given tuple, you need to iterate over the elements of the tuple and \
construct a new tuple that excludes the nested records. Below is a Python \
function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
remove_nested_records(input_tuple):\\n    # Use a tuple comprehension to \
filter out nested records\\n    # A nested record is considered as a list or \
a tuple\\n    return tuple(item for item in input_tuple if not \
isinstance(item, (list, tuple)))\\n\\n# Example usage\\noriginal_tuple = (1, \
2, (3, 4), [5, 6], 7, \\\"text\\\", (8, 9))\\nresult = \
remove_nested_records(original_tuple)\\nprint(result)  # Output: (1, 2, 7, \
'text')\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n\\n1. **Tuple Comprehension:** We loop \
through each element in the `input_tuple`.\\n2. **Type Checking:** For each \
element, we check if it is not an instance of `list` or `tuple`.\\n3. **Tuple \
Construction:** Only elements that are not lists or tuples are included in \
the new tuple.\\n4. **Return:** The function returns the new tuple with \
nested records removed.\\n\\nThis function will remove any nested tuples or \
lists from the given tuple, effectively flattening one level of nesting.\""}},
             GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
