              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the last position of an element in a sorted array, \
you can implement a binary search to efficiently locate the position. Here's \
a Python function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
find_last_position(arr, target):\\n    left, right = 0, len(arr) - 1\\n    \
result = -1\\n\\n    while left <= right:\\n        mid = left + (right - \
left) // 2\\n\\n        if arr[mid] == target:\\n            result = mid  # \
Update result and continue searching right\\n            left = mid + 1\\n    \
    elif arr[mid] < target:\\n            left = mid + 1\\n        else:\\n   \
         right = mid - 1\\n\\n    return result\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nsorted_array = [1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 4, 5]\\ntarget = \
2\\nprint(find_last_position(sorted_array, target))  # Output: \
3\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- Initialize `left` and `right` pointers for \
the binary search.\\n- The `result` variable keeps track of the last found \
position of the target.\\n- Use binary search:\\n  - If `arr[mid]` equals the \
target, update `result` and move the `left` pointer to `mid + 1` to search \
for any further occurrences.\\n  - Adjust `left` and `right` based on the \
comparison with the target.\\n- The loop terminates when `left` exceeds \
`right`, and `result` holds the last position of the target if found, \
otherwise `-1`.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
