              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a python function to left rotate the bits of a given \
number.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To left rotate the bits of a given number in Python, you can \
use bitwise operators. Here's a function that performs a left rotation on a \
32-bit integer:\\n\\n```python\\ndef left_rotate_bits(num, rotation, \
bit_width=32):\\n    # Mask to ensure the rotation does not exceed the bit \
width\\n    rotation = rotation % bit_width\\n    # Perform left rotation\\n  \
  rotated_num = (num << rotation) | (num >> (bit_width - rotation))\\n    # \
Mask to ensure the number is within the bit width (simulate overflow)\\n    \
rotated_num = rotated_num & ((1 << bit_width) - 1)\\n    return \
rotated_num\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nnumber = 0b1001  # Example binary \
number\\nrotation = 2     # Number of positions to rotate\\nresult = \
left_rotate_bits(number, rotation)\\nprint(bin(result))  # Output in binary \
format\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- **`rotation % bit_width`** ensures the \
rotation count does not exceed the bit width.\\n- **`(num << rotation)`** \
shifts bits to the left by the specified number of positions.\\n- **`(num >> \
(bit_width - rotation))`** handles the bits that overflow the left side and \
wraps them around to the right side.\\n- **`& ((1 << bit_width) - 1)`** masks \
the result to ensure it stays within the bounds of a 32-bit integer, \
simulating overflow behavior. Adjust `bit_width` as needed for different \
integer sizes.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a python function to left rotate the bits of a given \
number."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To left rotate the bits of a given number in Python, you can \
use bitwise operators. Here's a function that performs a left rotation on a \
32-bit integer:\n\n```python\ndef left_rotate_bits(num, rotation, \
bit_width=32):\n    # Mask to ensure the rotation does not exceed the bit \
width\n    rotation = rotation % bit_width\n    # Perform left rotation\n    \
rotated_num = (num << rotation) | (num >> (bit_width - rotation))\n    # Mask \
to ensure the number is within the bit width (simulate overflow)\n    \
rotated_num = rotated_num & ((1 << bit_width) - 1)\n    return rotated_num\n\n\
# Example usage:\nnumber = 0b1001  # Example binary number\nrotation = 2     \
# Number of positions to rotate\nresult = left_rotate_bits(number, rotation)\n\
print(bin(result))  # Output in binary format\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- \
**`rotation % bit_width`** ensures the rotation count does not exceed the bit \
width.\n- **`(num << rotation)`** shifts bits to the left by the specified \
number of positions.\n- **`(num >> (bit_width - rotation))`** handles the \
bits that overflow the left side and wraps them around to the right side.\n- \
**`& ((1 << bit_width) - 1)`** masks the result to ensure it stays within the \
bounds of a 32-bit integer, simulating overflow behavior. Adjust `bit_width` \
as needed for different integer sizes."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {
          400, Automatic}], "Tooltip"]& ], 
