           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a python function to count the number of rotations \
required to generate a sorted array.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To determine the number of rotations required to generate a \
sorted array from a rotated sorted array, you can find the index of the \
minimum element. This index represents the number of rotations. Here's a \
Python function to achieve this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
count_rotations(arr):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    This function finds the index \
of the minimum element in a rotated sorted array,\\n    which represents the \
number of rotations applied to the originally sorted array.\\n\\n    :param \
arr: List[int] - The input array that has been rotated.\\n    :return: int - \
The number of rotations.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    n = len(arr)\\n    \\n    # \
Handle empty array\\n    if n == 0:\\n        return 0\\n    \\n    # \
Initialize the left and right pointers for binary search\\n    left, right = \
0, n - 1\\n    \\n    # When the array is not rotated at all\\n    if \
arr[left] <= arr[right]:\\n        return 0\\n    \\n    # Perform binary \
search to find the rotation count\\n    while left <= right:\\n        mid = \
(left + right) // 2\\n        next_index = (mid + 1) % n\\n        prev_index \
= (mid - 1 + n) % n\\n        \\n        # Check if the mid element is the \
minimum (pivot point)\\n        if arr[mid] <= arr[next_index] and arr[mid] \
<= arr[prev_index]:\\n            return mid\\n        elif arr[mid] <= \
arr[right]:\\n            right = mid - 1\\n        else:\\n            left \
= mid + 1\\n    \\n    return 0  # Default return value, should not be \
reached\\n\\n# Example usage:\\n# rotated_array = [15, 18, 2, 3, 6, 12]\\n# \
print(count_rotations(rotated_array))  # Output: 2\\n```\\n\\nThis function \
uses binary search to efficiently find the index of the smallest element in \
the rotated sorted array. The index of this smallest element corresponds to \
the number of rotations needed to get back to the original sorted array.\""}},
             GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a python function to count the number of rotations \
required to generate a sorted array."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To determine the number of rotations required to generate a \
sorted array from a rotated sorted array, you can find the index of the \
minimum element. This index represents the number of rotations. Here's a \
Python function to achieve this:\n\n```python\ndef count_rotations(arr):\n    \
\"\"\"\n    This function finds the index of the minimum element in a rotated \
sorted array,\n    which represents the number of rotations applied to the \
originally sorted array.\n\n    :param arr: List[int] - The input array that \
has been rotated.\n    :return: int - The number of rotations.\n    \"\"\"\n  \
  n = len(arr)\n    \n    # Handle empty array\n    if n == 0:\n        \
return 0\n    \n    # Initialize the left and right pointers for binary \
search\n    left, right = 0, n - 1\n    \n    # When the array is not rotated \
at all\n    if arr[left] <= arr[right]:\n        return 0\n    \n    # \
Perform binary search to find the rotation count\n    while left <= right:\n  \
      mid = (left + right) // 2\n        next_index = (mid + 1) % n\n        \
prev_index = (mid - 1 + n) % n\n        \n        # Check if the mid element \
is the minimum (pivot point)\n        if arr[mid] <= arr[next_index] and \
arr[mid] <= arr[prev_index]:\n            return mid\n        elif arr[mid] \
<= arr[right]:\n            right = mid - 1\n        else:\n            left \
= mid + 1\n    \n    return 0  # Default return value, should not be reached\n\
\n# Example usage:\n# rotated_array = [15, 18, 2, 3, 6, 12]\n# \
print(count_rotations(rotated_array))  # Output: 2\n```\n\nThis function uses \
binary search to efficiently find the index of the smallest element in the \
rotated sorted array. The index of this smallest element corresponds to the \
number of rotations needed to get back to the original sorted array."}}, 
           Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {400, Automatic}], "Tooltip"]& ], 
