\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    return any(k in t for t in tuples_list)\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\ntuples = [(1, 2), (3, 4), (5, 6)]\\nk = 4\\nresult = \
contains_k(tuples, k)\\nprint(result)  # Output: True\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n- The function `contains_k` takes two parameters: \
`tuples_list` (a list of tuples) and `k` (the element to search for).\\n- It \
uses a generator expression `k in t for t in tuples_list` within the `any()` \
function to check if `k` is present in any tuple.\\n- `any()` returns `True` \
if at least one of the tuples contains `k`; otherwise, it returns \
`False`.\""}}, GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}},
