              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To create a function that checks if each element of the \
second tuple is smaller than its corresponding element in the first tuple, \
you can follow these steps:\\n\\n1. Ensure both tuples have the same \
length.\\n2. Iterate over the elements of both tuples simultaneously.\\n3. \
Compare each element of the second tuple with its corresponding element in \
the first tuple.\\n4. Return `True` if all elements in the second tuple are \
smaller; otherwise, return `False`.\\n\\nHere's a Python function that \
implements this logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef check_elements_smaller(tuple1, \
tuple2):\\n    # Check if both tuples are of the same length\\n    if \
len(tuple1) != len(tuple2):\\n        raise ValueError(\\\"Tuples must be of \
the same length\\\")\\n    \\n    # Iterate through both tuples and compare \
elements\\n    for elem1, elem2 in zip(tuple1, tuple2):\\n        if elem2 >= \
elem1:\\n            return False\\n    \\n    return True\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\ntuple1 = (10, 20, 30)\\ntuple2 = (5, 15, 25)\\nresult = \
check_elements_smaller(tuple1, tuple2)\\nprint(result)  # Output: \
True\\n```\\n\\nThis function will raise a `ValueError` if the tuples are not \
of the same length, ensuring the precondition for comparison is met. It \
returns `True` if every element in the second tuple is smaller than its \
counterpart in the first tuple, and `False` otherwise.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
