              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to count the frequency of consecutive \
duplicate elements in a given list of numbers.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Certainly! You can write a Python function to count the \
frequency of consecutive duplicate elements in a list. Here's a concise \
implementation:\\n\\n```python\\ndef count_consecutive_duplicates(nums):\\n   \
 if not nums:\\n        return []\\n    \\n    result = []\\n    current_num \
= nums[0]\\n    count = 1\\n\\n    for num in nums[1:]:\\n        if num == \
current_num:\\n            count += 1\\n        else:\\n            \
result.append((current_num, count))\\n            current_num = num\\n        \
    count = 1\\n    result.append((current_num, count))  # Add the last group\
\\n\\n    return result\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nnums = [1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 3, 3, \
4, 1, 1]\\nprint(count_consecutive_duplicates(nums))\\n```\\n\\n### \
Explanation:\\n- The function `count_consecutive_duplicates` takes a list of \
numbers `nums` as input.\\n- It checks if the list is empty and returns an \
empty list if true.\\n- It initializes a `result` list to store the tuples of \
each number and its consecutive count.\\n- It uses `current_num` to keep \
track of the current number being counted and `count` to keep track of its \
frequency.\\n- It iterates over the list starting from the second element. If \
the current element is the same as `current_num`, it increments the \
`count`.\\n- If a different number appears, it appends a tuple `(current_num, \
