              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to check if the given string starts with a \
substring using regex.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To check if a given string starts with a specific substring \
using regular expressions in Python, you can use the `re` module. Here's a \
function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\nimport re\\n\\ndef \
starts_with_substring(s, substring):\\n    # Use the '^' symbol to indicate \
the start of the string in the regex pattern\\n    pattern = \
f'^{re.escape(substring)}'\\n    # Use re.match to check if the pattern \
matches the start of the string\\n    return re.match(pattern, s) is not None\
\\n\\n# Example usage:\\n# print(starts_with_substring(\\\"hello world\\\", \
\\\"hello\\\"))  # Output: True\\n# print(starts_with_substring(\\\"hello \
world\\\", \\\"world\\\"))  # Output: False\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- \
**`re.escape(substring)`**: Escapes any special characters in the substring \
to ensure they are treated as literal characters in the regular \
expression.\\n- **`'^'`**: Anchors the pattern to the start of the \
string.\\n- **`re.match`**: Attempts to match the pattern from the start of \
the string. If it matches, it returns a match object; otherwise, it returns \
`None`.\\n- **`re.match(...) is not None`**: Returns `True` if the match is \
successful, indicating the string starts with the specified substring, and \
`False` otherwise.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
          ImageSize -> {400, Automatic}]], Annotation[#, 
         Pane[
          Grid[{{
             Style["Prompt:", Bold], 
             "Write a function to check if the given string starts with a \
substring using regex."}, {
             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "To check if a given string starts with a specific substring \
using regular expressions in Python, you can use the `re` module. Here's a \
function that accomplishes this:\n\n```python\nimport re\n\ndef \
starts_with_substring(s, substring):\n    # Use the '^' symbol to indicate \
the start of the string in the regex pattern\n    pattern = \
f'^{re.escape(substring)}'\n    # Use re.match to check if the pattern \
matches the start of the string\n    return re.match(pattern, s) is not None\n\
\n# Example usage:\n# print(starts_with_substring(\"hello world\", \
\"hello\"))  # Output: True\n# print(starts_with_substring(\"hello world\", \
\"world\"))  # Output: False\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- \
**`re.escape(substring)`**: Escapes any special characters in the substring \
to ensure they are treated as literal characters in the regular expression.\n\
- **`'^'`**: Anchors the pattern to the start of the string.\n- \
**`re.match`**: Attempts to match the pattern from the start of the string. \
If it matches, it returns a match object; otherwise, it returns `None`.\n- \
**`re.match(...) is not None`**: Returns `True` if the match is successful, \
indicating the string starts with the specified substring, and `False` \
otherwise."}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {400, Automatic}], "Tooltip"]& ], 
