be resolved with one swap, and any remaining mismatches (odd count) cannot be \
resolved.\\n\\nHere's the Python function that implements this \
logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef min_swaps_to_make_equal(s1, s2):\\n    if len(s1) \
!= len(s2):\\n        return -1  # Strings of different lengths cannot be \
made equal with swaps\\n\\n    # Mismatches counts\\n    count_01 = 0\\n    \
count_10 = 0\\n\\n    # Count mismatches\\n    for c1, c2 in zip(s1, s2):\\n  \
      if c1 == '0' and c2 == '1':\\n            count_01 += 1\\n        elif \
c1 == '1' and c2 == '0':\\n            count_10 += 1\\n\\n    # To make the \
strings equal, the number of '01' mismatches must equal '10' mismatches\\n    \
if (count_01 + count_10) % 2 != 0:\\n        return -1  # Unequal number of \
'01' and '10' mismatches means it's impossible\\n\\n    # Each pair of '01' \
and '10' can be swapped once\\n    swaps = count_01 // 2 + count_10 // 2\\n   \
 # If there's one extra '01' and '10' pair, we need one more swap\\n    if \
count_01 % 2 != 0:\\n        swaps += 2\\n\\n    return swaps\\n\\n# Example \
usage\\ns1 = \\\"1100\\\"\\ns2 = \
\\\"1001\\\"\\nprint(min_swaps_to_make_equal(s1, s2))  # Output: \
1\\n```\\n\\nThis function first checks if the strings are of equal length \
