              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the number that occurs an odd number of times in an \
array, you can use a simple and efficient approach leveraging the XOR \
operation. The XOR operation has the property where `x ^ x = 0` and `x ^ 0 = \
x`. Moreover, XOR is commutative and associative, which means the order of \
operations does not matter.\\n\\nHere's a Python function that implements \
this logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef find_odd_occurrence(arr):\\n    result = \
0\\n    for number in arr:\\n        result ^= number\\n    return \
result\\n\\n# Example usage:\\narray = [1, 2, 3, 2, 3, 1, \
3]\\nodd_occurrence_number = \
find_odd_occurrence(array)\\nprint(odd_occurrence_number)  # Output will be 3\
\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. Initialize `result` to 0.\\n2. Iterate \
through each number in the array, XORing it with `result`.\\n3. After \
processing all numbers, `result` will hold the number that appears an odd \
number of times, since all numbers that appear an even number of times will \
cancel out (i.e., their XOR will be 0).\\n\\nThis approach works efficiently \
in O(n) time complexity and O(1) space complexity.\""}}, 
