              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To generate all sublists of a given list, you can use a \
function that iterates through all possible combinations of indices. Here's a \
Python function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
generate_sublists(input_list):\\n    # This will hold all the sublists\\n    \
sublists = []\\n    # Get the length of the input list\\n    n = \
len(input_list)\\n    # Iterate over all possible starting indices\\n    for \
start in range(n):\\n        # Iterate over all possible ending indices\\n    \
    for end in range(start + 1, n + 1):\\n            # Append the sublist \
from start to end (exclusive) to the result\\n            \
sublists.append(input_list[start:end])\\n    return sublists\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nexample_list = [1, 2, 3]\\nresult = \
generate_sublists(example_list)\\nprint(result)\\n```\\n\\nThis function \
works by iterating over all possible starting and ending indices in the list \
and extracting the sublist for each pair of indices. Note that this includes \
all sublists of length 1 up to the length of the list. If you want to include \
the empty sublist as well, you can simply append `[]` to the `sublists` list \
at the beginning.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
