           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a function to find the length of the longest \
sub-sequence such that elements in the subsequences are consecutive integers.\
\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the length of the longest subsequence of consecutive \
integers within an array, you can use the following approach:\\n\\n1. Use a \
set to eliminate duplicates and allow O(1) average time complexity for \
lookups.\\n2. Iterate over each element in the array.\\n3. For each element, \
check if it's the start of a consecutive sequence (i.e., the element minus \
one is not present in the set).\\n4. If it is the start, count the length of \
the sequence by incrementing a counter and checking consecutive \
elements.\\n5. Track the maximum length of all such sequences.\\n\\nHere's \
the Python function implementing this logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
longest_consecutive_subsequence(arr):\\n    if not arr:\\n        return 0\\n\
\\n    num_set = set(arr)\\n    max_length = 0\\n\\n    for num in \
num_set:\\n        # Check if it's the start of a sequence\\n        if num - \
1 not in num_set:\\n            current_length = 1\\n            current_num \
= num\\n\\n            # Count the length of the sequence\\n            while \
current_num + 1 in num_set:\\n                current_num += 1\\n             \
   current_length += 1\\n\\n            # Update the maximum length found\\n  \
          max_length = max(max_length, current_length)\\n\\n    return \
max_length\\n\\n# Example usage:\\n# arr = [100, 4, 200, 1, 3, 2]\\n# \
print(longest_consecutive_subsequence(arr))  # Output: 4\\n```\\n\\nThis \
function efficiently finds the length of the longest subsequence of \
consecutive integers by leveraging a set for fast lookups and only counting \
sequences from their starting points. The overall time complexity is O(n), \
where n is the number of elements in the array.\""}}, 
