              "\"Write a function to find palindromes in a given list of \
strings using lambda function.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Certainly! You can use a lambda function in combination with \
the `filter` function to find palindromes in a list of strings. Here's a \
Python function that accomplishes this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef \
find_palindromes(words):\\n    return list(filter(lambda word: word == \
word[::-1], words))\\n\\n# Example usage:\\nwords_list = [\\\"radar\\\", \
\\\"hello\\\", \\\"level\\\", \\\"world\\\", \\\"madam\\\", \
\\\"python\\\"]\\npalindromes = \
find_palindromes(words_list)\\nprint(palindromes)  # Output: ['radar', \
'level', 'madam']\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n\\n- `filter(function, \
iterable)` is used to filter elements from the iterable for which the \
function returns `True`.\\n- The lambda function `lambda word: word == \
word[::-1]` checks if a string (word) is equal to its reverse (`word[::-1]`).\
\\n- The `filter` function applies this lambda to each element in the `words` \
list and returns an iterator of all elements that satisfy the palindrome \
condition.\\n- `list()` is used to convert the iterator into a list of \
palindromes.\\n\\nThis function effectively finds and returns all palindrome \
words from the given list.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
