              "\"To determine if two strings are rotations of each other, you \
can concatenate one of the strings with itself and then check if the other \
string appears as a substring within this concatenated result. Here's a \
Python function to accomplish this:\\n\\n```python\\ndef are_rotations(s1, \
s2):\\n    if len(s1) != len(s2):\\n        return False\\n    concatenated = \
s1 + s1\\n    return s2 in concatenated\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nprint(are_rotations(\\\"abcde\\\", \\\"deabc\\\"))  # Output: \
True\\nprint(are_rotations(\\\"abcde\\\", \\\"edcba\\\"))  # Output: \
False\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. **Length Check:** First, check if the \
two strings have the same length. If not, they cannot be rotations of each \
other.\\n2. **Concatenation:** If they are of equal length, concatenate `s1` \
with itself.\\n3. **Substring Check:** Verify if `s2` is a substring of the \
concatenated result. If it is, `s2` is a rotation of `s1`; otherwise, it is \
not.\""}}, GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
