Fibonacci sequence using recursion:\n\n```python\ndef fibonacci(n):\n    if n \
<= 0:\n        return \"Input should be a positive integer\"\n    elif n == \
1:\n        return 0\n    elif n == 2:\n        return 1\n    else:\n        \
return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2)\n\n# Example usage:\n# \
print(fibonacci(10))  # Output: 34\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- The function \
`fibonacci` takes an integer `n` as input.\n- If `n` is less than or equal to \
0, it returns an error message, since the Fibonacci sequence is defined for \
positive integers.\n- For `n = 1`, it returns 0, since the first Fibonacci \
number is 0.\n- For `n = 2`, it returns 1, since the second Fibonacci number \
is 1.\n- For `n > 2`, it recursively calls itself to compute the sum of the \
two preceding numbers in the sequence.\n\nThis function will compute the nth \
Fibonacci number using the recursive formula: \n\n\\[ F(n) = F(n-1) + F(n-2) \
\\]\n\nNote that this recursive approach is not the most efficient for large \
`n` due to repeated calculations, and a dynamic programming or iterative \
approach would be more efficient in such cases."}}, 
