              "\"To reverse each list within a given list of lists, you can \
define a function in Python. Here's a simple \
implementation:\\n\\n```python\\ndef reverse_lists(list_of_lists):\\n    # \
Use a list comprehension to reverse each list in the list_of_lists.\\n    \
return [lst[::-1] for lst in list_of_lists]\\n\\n# Example \
usage:\\nexample_list_of_lists = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6], [7, 8, \
9]]\\nreversed_lists = \
reverse_lists(example_list_of_lists)\\nprint(reversed_lists)  # Output: [[3, \
2, 1], [6, 5, 4], [9, 8, 7]]\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n- The function \
`reverse_lists` takes a single argument `list_of_lists`, which is expected to \
be a list containing other lists.\\n- A list comprehension is used to iterate \
over each sublist (`lst`) in `list_of_lists`.\\n- Each sublist is reversed \
using slicing (`lst[::-1]`).\\n- The result is a new list containing each \
reversed sublist.\\n\\nThis approach efficiently reverses each sublist while \
maintaining the overall structure of the list of lists.\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
