         PaneBox[
          TagBox[
           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"Write a python function to find the index of an extra \
element present in one sorted array.\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To find the index of an extra element present in one of two \
sorted arrays, you can use a binary search approach to efficiently identify \
the position of the mismatch. Below is a Python function that implements this \
logic:\\n\\n```python\\ndef find_extra_element_index(arr1, arr2):\\n    \
\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    Find the index of the extra element present in the longer \
sorted array.\\n    \\n    :param arr1: List[int] - The shorter sorted array.\
\\n    :param arr2: List[int] - The longer sorted array with one extra \
element.\\n    :return: int - The index of the extra element in the longer \
array.\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    # Ensure arr2 is the longer array\\n    if \
len(arr1) > len(arr2):\\n        arr1, arr2 = arr2, arr1\\n\\n    left, right \
= 0, len(arr1)\\n\\n    # Perform binary search\\n    while left < right:\\n  \
      mid = (left + right) // 2\\n        if arr1[mid] == arr2[mid]:\\n       \
     left = mid + 1\\n        else:\\n            right = mid\\n\\n    # The \
left index will point to the extra element\\n    return left\\n\\n# Example \
Usage\\narr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\\narr2 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\\nindex = \
find_extra_element_index(arr1, arr2)\\nprint(f\\\"The index of the extra \
element is: {index}\\\")\\n```\\n\\n### Explanation:\\n1. **Input \
Validation:** Ensure `arr2` is the longer array. If not, swap the \
arrays.\\n2. **Binary Search:** Use a binary search to find the index where \
the elements in `arr1` and `arr2` start to differ.\\n   - If `arr1[mid]` \
equals `arr2[mid]`, the extra element is further right, so move `left` to \
`mid + 1`.\\n   - Otherwise, the extra element might be at or before `mid`, \
so adjust `right` to `mid`.\\n3. **Result:** The variable `left` will point \
to the index of the extra element in the longer array when the loop \
terminates.\""}}, 
