the maximum sum at each index\n    n = len(arr)\n    max_sum = [0] * n\n    \n\
    # Initialize the first two values\n    max_sum[0] = arr[0]\n    \
max_sum[1] = max(arr[0], arr[1])\n    \n    # Fill the max_sum array\n    for \
i in range(2, n):\n        # Either take the current element and add it to \
the max_sum[i-2]\n        # or skip the current element and take the \
max_sum[i-1]\n        max_sum[i] = max(arr[i] + max_sum[i-2], max_sum[i-1])\n \
   \n    # The last element contains the result\n    return max_sum[-1]\n\n# \
Example usage:\narr = [3, 2, 7, 10]\nresult = max_sum_no_adjacent(arr)\n\
print(result)  # Output: 13\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Base Cases**: \n   \
- If the array is empty, the maximum sum is 0.\n   - If the array has one \
element, the maximum sum is the value of that element.\n\n2. **Dynamic \
Programming Array**:\n   - `max_sum[i]` represents the maximum sum of \
subsequences from the start of the array up to index `i`, without taking \
adjacent elements.\n\n3. **Recurrence Relation**:\n   - For each element \
`arr[i]`, decide whether to include it in the sum:\n     - If included, add \
it to `max_sum[i-2]` (since `arr[i-1]` cannot be included).\n     - If not \
included, carry forward the maximum sum up to `i-1`, i.e., `max_sum[i-1]`.\n  \
 - The formula is: `max_sum[i] = max(arr[i] + max_sum[i-2], max_sum[i-1])`.\n\
\n4. **Result**:\n   - The last entry in"}}, Alignment -> {Left, Top}], {
