           GridBox[{{
              StyleBox["\"Prompt:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"If it rains, then the ground gets wet. We observe that the \
ground is wet. What can we infer?\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"The statement \\\"If it rains, then the ground gets wet\\\" \
is a conditional statement. Observing that the ground is wet does not \
necessarily mean that it rained, because there could be other reasons for the \
ground being wet (e.g., someone watering the garden, a sprinkler system, \
etc.).\\n\\nTherefore, while the ground being wet is consistent with it \
having rained, it is not sufficient to conclude that it must have rained. \
This is an example of the logical fallacy known as \\\"affirming the \
consequent.\\\"\\n\\n**Final Answer: We cannot definitively conclude that it \
rained; the ground could be wet for other reasons.**\""}}, 
            GridBoxAlignment -> {"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Top}}}, 
            AutoDelete -> False, 
            GridBoxItemSize -> {
             "Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}], "Grid"], 
