             Style["Response:", Bold], 
             "The statement \"If it rains, then the ground gets wet\" is a \
conditional statement. Observing that the ground is wet does not necessarily \
mean that it rained, because there could be other reasons for the ground \
being wet (e.g., someone watering the garden, a sprinkler system, etc.).\n\n\
Therefore, while the ground being wet is consistent with it having rained, it \
is not sufficient to conclude that it must have rained. This is an example of \
the logical fallacy known as \"affirming the consequent.\"\n\n**Final Answer: \
