              "\"By the time Anne is two times as old as Emile, Emile will be \
six times as old as Maude. If Maude will be 8 years old, how old will Anne \
be?\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To solve this problem, we need to set up equations based on \
the given relationships. Let's define the current ages of Anne, Emile, and \
Maude as \\\\( A \\\\), \\\\( E \\\\), and \\\\( M \\\\) respectively. \
\\n\\nWe are given that Maude will be 8 years old at the time when Anne is \
twice as old as Emile, and Emile is six times as old as Maude. Let's denote \
the number of years from now when this will happen as \\\\( x \\\\).\\n\\nAt \
that future time:\\n- Maude's age will be \\\\( M + x = 8 \\\\).\\n- Emile's \
age will be \\\\( E + x \\\\).\\n- Anne's age will be \\\\( A + x \
\\\\).\\n\\nWe have the following relationships:\\n1. \\\\( A + x = 2(E + x) \
\\\\) (Anne will be twice as old as Emile).\\n2. \\\\( E + x = 6(M + x) \\\\) \
(Emile will be six times as old as Maude).\\n\\nFrom the first equation:\\n\\\
\\[ A + x = 2E + 2x \\\\]\\n\\\\[ A = 2E + x \\\\]\\n\\nFrom the second \
equation:\\n\\\\[ E + x = 6 \\\\times 8 \\\\]\\n\\\\[ E + x = 48 \
\\\\]\\n\\\\[ E = 48 - x \\\\]\\n\\nSubstitute \\\\( E = 48 - x \\\\) into \
the equation \\\\( A = 2E + x \\\\):\\n\\\\[ A = 2(48 - x) + x \\\\]\\n\\\\[ \
A = 96 - 2x + x \\\\]\\n\\\\[ A = 96 - x \\\\]\\n\\nWe also know from \\\\( M \
+ x = 8 \\\\) that \\\\( x = 8 - M \\\\). Replace \\\\( x \\\\) in \\\\( A = \
96 - x \\\\):\\n\\\\[ A = 96 - (8 - M) \\\\]\\n\\\\[ A = 96 - 8 + M \
\\\\]\\n\\\\[ A = 88 + M \\\\]\\n\\nSince Maude will be 8 years old at that \
time, \\\\( M = 8 - x \\\\). We previously found \\\\( x = 8 - M \\\\), so \\\
\\( M = 0 \\\\) (Maude is currently 0 years old).\\n\\nThus, the age of Anne \
when Maude will be 8 years old is:\\n\\\\[ A = 88 + 0 = 88 \
\\\\]\\n\\nTherefore, Anne will be 88 years old. \\n\\nFinal answer\""}}, 
