September?\""}, {
              StyleBox["\"Response:\"", Bold, StripOnInput -> False], 
              "\"To determine how many bales of hay the farmer will have left \
by the end of December, we need to follow these steps:\\n\\n1. **Calculate \
the Total Harvest for This Year:**\\n   - Last year, the farmer harvested 560 \
bales from 5 acres. This gives a yield of 112 bales per acre (560 bales / 5 \
acres).\\n   - This year, the farmer has 5 + 7 = 12 acres.\\n   - Therefore, \
the total harvest this year will be \\\\( 12 \\\\, \\\\text{acres} \\\\times \
112 \\\\, \\\\text{bales/acre} = 1344 \\\\) bales.\\n\\n2. **Determine the \
Total Consumption by the Horses:**\\n   - The farmer owns 9 horses, and each \
horse consumes 3 bales per day.\\n   - Total daily consumption for the horses \
is \\\\( 9 \\\\, \\\\text{horses} \\\\times 3 \\\\, \\\\text{bales/horse/day} \
= 27 \\\\) bales per day.\\n   - The period from September 1 to December 31 \
is 4 months.\\n   - Assuming September, October, November, and December have \
30, 31, 30, and 31 days respectively, the total number of days is \\\\( 30 + \
31 + 30 + 31 = 122 \\\\) days.\\n   - Therefore, the total consumption over \
these 122 days is \\\\( 122 \\\\, \\\\text{days} \\\\times 27 \\\\, \
\\\\text{bales/day} = 3294 \\\\) bales.\\n\\n3. **Calculate the Remaining \
Bales of Hay:**\\n   - Start with 1344 bales from this year's harvest.\\n   - \
Subtract the 3294 bales consumed by the horses: \\n     \\\\[\\n     1344 - \
3294 = -1950\\n     \\\\]\\n\\nSince the result is negative, it indicates \
